{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_amaryllis_ver01/data/sn88077226/00414210387/1949032901/0964.xml":{"full_text":"Page Two\nThe OHIO DAILY EXPRESS\nPublished ivtry evening except Sunday bj Paige H. Stnokland at\n1007 Germantown street, Dayton 7. Ohio. Phone HEmlock 1076.\nPAIGE H. STRICKLAND Editor and Publisher\n1AYMOND SWANN Advertising Manager\nNATIONAL ADVERTISING, Interstate United Newspapers, Inc.\n646 Fifth Avenue, New York 17, New York\nThe Labor View\nBy George P. MeCfay for AMP\nA week ago I addressed a pub\nlic forum at a settlement house\nin Chicago. One of the other\nspeakers that evening was Jack\nStaehl, industrial relations direc\ntor for one of the largest mail\norder houses in the world. The\nsubject we discussed was \"Can\nNegroes Hold Their Gains In Bus\niness and Industry?\" He thinks\nwe can.\nInevitably the discussion turned\nto the question of anti-Negro dis\ncrimination in unions, among em\nployers, and what might be done\nabout this evil.\nMr. Smith reported that his\ncompany started employing Negro\nclerical workers in large numbers\nfor the first time during the war.\nToday about a half of their sever\nal thousands employees are young\nNegro women engaged as order\nfillers, cashiers, mail openers and\nsorters, file clerks, packers,\ncheckers and other clerical work\ners. Other mail order houses in\nChicago also employ large num\nbers of Negro clerical workers,\nbut the records \"of those compan\nies are not quite as good as the\none at the plant where Mr. Smith\nis employed.\nDuring the question period, an\nalert questioner asked why white\nemployers always lay off Negro\nworkers first they seemed to be\ndoing at the present time?\nMr. Smith reported he did not\nthink white employers always did\nsuch things. He knows many\nwhite employers who are scrupu\nlously fair in their dealing with\nNegro workers and such Negroes\nreward fair treatment with better\nand more efficient work.\nTo illustrate his point, hie stat\ned that his company during the\ncurrent recession had discharged\nmore white workers than Negroes.\nHe said that his company, like oth\ner businesses is interested primar\nily in profits and that in a high\nly competitive business like the\nmail order business, labor must\nbe swift\nrf\nand efficient if profits\nare to be realized.\nProduction records revealed, he\nsaid, that the Negro workers on\nthe whole were far more efficient\nthan white workers. It would\nhave been foolish and unprofit\nable to have laid off efficient\nNegr helpo while keeping less ef\nficient white. He said also that a\nlong policy of equal treatment for\nboth Negroes and white workers\nhad assured Negroes that advance\nment in the business would de\npend not upon their color but up\non their ability. The policy is\npaying off in higher profits.\nMADAM LAMAR\n5724 West Third Street\nPkone ME 7607\nReader and Adviser\nSpecial Reading\n$1.00\nI give never failing advice\nupon all matters of life, such\nas love, courtship, marriage, di\nvorce, business transactions of\nall kinds. I never fail to reunite\nthe separated, cause speedy and\nhappy marriages, overcome en\nemies, rivals, lover's quarrels,\nevil habits, stumbling blocks,\nand bad luck of all kinds. I\nlift you out of sorrow and\ntroubles and start you on the\npath of happiness and prosper\nity. There is no heart so bad\nor home so dreary that I can\nnot bring sunshine in it. In\nfact, no matter what may be\nyour hope, fear or ambition, I\nguarantee to tell it all before\nyou utter a word to me and\nafter I am finished if you are\nnot entirely satisfied and if 1\ndo not faithfully fulfill every\nclaim above, then you pay me\nnot a penny.\nBIG BENEFITS\nwith CLASSIFIED\nADVERTISING\nPin your copy with remittance to thi*\u00a3orm aud amil to\nCLASSIFIED ADV. DEPT.\nTHE OHIO DAILY EXPRESS,\n1007 Germantown Street, Dayton 7, Ohio.\nYour Name\nAddress\nNumber of Insertions.\nShall we use Key No.1L\nRATES\u201420c a line per insertion, minimum 2 lines, unkeyed. Add\n20c per insertion for keyed ads. Situations Wanted\u201420c a line per\ntPMrtion, minimum 2 lines, unkeyed. Keyed\u201440c a line, plus 20c\nkeying charge. Figure five words (of five letters each) to the flnrt\nline and five words (of six letters each to subsequent linew\nOHIO DAILY EXPRESS\nElks Leader\nBuried In Seattle\nSEATTLE, Wash., March 28. (A\nNP)\u2014Jay Chavis, 56, grand es\nquire of the Improved Benevolent\nProtective Order of Elks of the\nWorld, was* buried here last week.\nHe died Sunday, March 13 at the\nTacoma General hospital, in Ta\ncoma.\nFuneral sendees were held at\nthe E. R. Butterworth funeral\nhome, and burial ceremonies at\nLake View cemetery.\nAmong the Elk leaflets' attend\ning the funeral were Dr. J. Fin\nley Wilson, grand exalted ruler,\nWashington, D. C. Judge Wil\nliam C. Houston, grand commis\nsioner of education, Gary, Ind.,\nand James E. Kelley, grand lodge\n(continued on page 3)\nHOTEL IRMA JEAN\n353-55 West Fifth Street\nDayton 2, Ohio\nI'\nFood and Soft\nDrink Bear\nReasonable Rates\nHerman Carter, Proprietor\nPhone: ADams 0630 S\n................11\n1124 West\nFifth Street\nBREAKFASTS\n40c\nH. T. STARK'S GARAGE\nWheel Balancing, Front End Work, Lubrication, Motor Tum or\nOverhall, Transmission Clutch Overhaul, and\nGenerator Service\nSPECIALIZED BU1CK SERVIICt\nPhone ADams 5021 608 S. Summit St. (Rear)\n...WilfBeAt\nYour Service\nPRESTON'S\n24-Hour Service\nDRUG STORE\nJUST DIAL\nMI 7061\nTHE\nJUST-US-CLUB\n\"SERVES THE BEST FOOD IN TOWN AT\nTHE LOWEST PRICES ANYWHERE AROUND\"\nLUNCHEONS\n60c\nOPEN 7 A. M. DAILY\nLuncheons and Dinner Served\nPromptly at 11 A. M.\nS E I A\nDining Rooms for Your\nPrivate Parties\nJust Call\nAD 0095\nTuesday, M^roh 29, 194$\nAD 0095\nDINNERS\n60c\n1","height":"19821","width":"15075"}}
